1. URL (Uniform Resource Locator)

A URL is the address of a resource on the Internet.

Example:

https://www.google.com

The browser reads this address to determine which website you want to visit.

2. Browser

A browser is software used to access websites.

Examples:

Google Chrome
Mozilla Firefox
Microsoft Edge
Brave
Safari

The browser acts as the client because it requests information from a server.

3. DNS Lookup

Humans remember names like:

google.com

Computers communicate using IP addresses like:

142.250.xxx.xxx

DNS (Domain Name System) converts a domain name into an IP address.

Example:

google.com
        │
        ▼
142.250.xxx.xxx

Real-life analogy

DNS is like your phone's contact list.

You search for Mom, but your phone actually dials a phone number.

4. TCP Connection

Once the browser knows the server's IP address, it creates a TCP connection.

This starts with the Three-Way Handshake.

SYN
 │
 ▼
SYN-ACK
 │
 ▼
ACK

Only after this handshake can reliable communication begin.

5. HTTPS & TLS

Most websites today use HTTPS.

HTTPS is simply HTTP secured using TLS encryption.

TLS protects sensitive information while it travels across the Internet.

Examples:

Passwords
Cookies
Credit Card Details
Personal Information

Without HTTPS, attackers could read or modify transmitted data.

6. HTTP Request

After the connection is established, the browser sends an HTTP Request.

Example:

GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: google.com
User-Agent: Chrome

Think of it as saying:

"Hello Google, please send me your homepage."

7. Server Processing

The server receives the request and processes it.

Depending on the request, it may:

Retrieve files
Query a database
Verify authentication
Check user permissions
Execute application logic

Finally, it prepares a response.

8. HTTP Response

The server replies with an HTTP Response.

Example:

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/html

The response may contain:

HTML
CSS
JavaScript
Images
Fonts
Status Code
Headers
9. Browser Rendering

After receiving the response, the browser starts building the webpage.

It downloads and processes:

HTML
CSS
JavaScript
Images
Fonts

Finally, it displays the complete website on your screen.

